WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.840
Good morning. Let me start with a question. What do you think is the most important aspect

00:00:12.840 --> 00:00:17.719
of using R successfully? Is it being able to write high-performance code, or making

00:00:17.719 --> 00:00:23.260
beautiful graphics, or perhaps learning how to write R packages? Here's my take on it.

00:00:23.260 --> 00:00:28.740
I think the most important aspect of using R successfully is being able to find and choose

00:00:28.740 --> 00:00:33.740
the right tools for the job that you're working on. I think a lot of data science projects,

00:00:33.740 --> 00:00:39.500
they get stuck, or they're not as successful as they could be because they chose the wrong

00:00:39.500 --> 00:00:45.419
tools in the project to build on. Once you've gone with a certain tool, it can be very hard

00:00:45.419 --> 00:00:50.939
to go back and fix that. My name is Jeroen Ooms. I've written quite a few R packages,

00:00:50.939 --> 00:00:55.139
some of which you may have used. I'm also the maintainer of the compilers and the build

00:00:55.139 --> 00:01:02.220
infrastructure for R on Windows. I'm a staff member of the R OpenSci group at UC Berkeley.

00:01:02.220 --> 00:01:08.379
Within R OpenSci, we're working on a big ambitious new project called R Universe. In essence,

00:01:08.379 --> 00:01:14.900
R Universe is an open platform based on Git for managing personal R package repositories.

00:01:14.900 --> 00:01:18.739
That means that once a package is registered, the system will automatically build binaries

00:01:18.820 --> 00:01:26.660
and documentation and so on directly from Git every time the package author pushes an update.

00:01:26.660 --> 00:01:32.260
These can be R packages that are also on CRAN or Bioconductor or just your personal R packages.

00:01:32.260 --> 00:01:38.739
That really doesn't matter as long as the source code is available from Git. However,

00:01:38.739 --> 00:01:43.820
publishing packages is actually not the goal of this project. More importantly, it is a

00:01:43.820 --> 00:01:51.300
starting point for us to experiment with calculating metrics and showing other background

00:01:51.300 --> 00:01:57.220
information about a package that may tell us something about the health and the role

00:01:57.220 --> 00:02:02.580
and the impact of a particular project. Towards the end of this talk, I will briefly

00:02:02.580 --> 00:02:08.339
explain what R Universe does and where this is coming from. But mostly today, I want to

00:02:08.339 --> 00:02:13.779
talk about why we believe it is important to have better tooling to actively monitor

00:02:13.779 --> 00:02:19.860
the status and the health of research software. Because I think there are some important differences

00:02:19.860 --> 00:02:26.339
between using open source software and commercial software that are not always immediately obvious.

00:02:26.339 --> 00:02:32.179
In particular, when it comes to expectations about the quality and the lifecycle and the

00:02:32.179 --> 00:02:38.820
participation in open source projects. So, I hope to make you think a little bit about

00:02:39.460 --> 00:02:43.139
things you may want to consider when you're going to use open source software

00:02:43.779 --> 00:02:47.539
and some indicators that you may want to look for in a healthy project.

00:02:48.580 --> 00:02:53.619
So, how do we discover and choose the best R packages? Because R is amazing and you can do

00:02:53.619 --> 00:02:58.820
so many cool things with it and there's very few rules or limitations. But this also makes

00:02:58.899 --> 00:03:04.020
our ecosystem sometimes feel a bit like the Wild West of research software, where it can be very

00:03:04.020 --> 00:03:10.020
hard to find the good stuff or to judge if something is trustworthy. Suppose you're a data

00:03:10.020 --> 00:03:15.300
scientist and you need to do a particular analysis or you need to read a particular file format or

00:03:15.300 --> 00:03:22.660
you need an HTTP client to interface to some open data web servers. How do you know what's out there

00:03:22.660 --> 00:03:27.300
and how do you know if it's any good? Maybe you find an article or a blog post that mentions

00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:33.220
an interesting package. So, you read the description and you maybe run an example and it seems to work.

00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:39.059
So, problem solved, right? Well, as you probably know, anyone can create an R package. You just put

00:03:39.059 --> 00:03:43.300
your code into the right format and then you pull it up on GitHub or you submit it to CRAN.

00:03:43.300 --> 00:03:47.860
Now, CRAN will actually check if the package can be installed on Windows and Mac and Linux

00:03:47.860 --> 00:03:54.899
and if it does not violate any policies. But that's about it. There's no gatekeeping or judgment on

00:03:54.899 --> 00:04:00.419
the contents of the R package. And this is what makes open source software so great because anyone

00:04:00.419 --> 00:04:08.580
can participate. But obviously, the quality of these contributions can vary. And what is perhaps

00:04:08.580 --> 00:04:15.139
less obvious at first is that different package authors have very different ideas on what you can

00:04:15.139 --> 00:04:21.540
expect from them in terms of maintenance and support and participation. And these things

00:04:21.540 --> 00:04:26.899
become more relevant as you start using R more seriously. Now, of course, when you're just toying

00:04:26.899 --> 00:04:31.540
around for a homework assignment or a one-off problem, you just do whatever works and move on.

00:04:32.660 --> 00:04:38.660
But if you start to really depend on a package, I think the dynamic changes a bit. Suppose you're

00:04:38.660 --> 00:04:42.980
really going to build an R package in your dissertation research or your company's data

00:04:42.980 --> 00:04:48.100
pipeline. At some point, you should probably ask yourself some questions like who made this package?

00:04:48.739 --> 00:04:54.260
What's their background? Is this an expert? What other things have they made? And how can you trust

00:04:54.260 --> 00:04:59.299
the results are correct? Has there been any peer review or scientific publication to accompany this

00:04:59.299 --> 00:05:05.380
package? Is it reliable? Does it get tested a lot? Because if it works for one example, that doesn't

00:05:05.380 --> 00:05:10.579
always mean it's going to work for any data. And what if you have a question about the software or

00:05:10.579 --> 00:05:15.940
you find a bug? Is the maintainer going to be available to help you? Is the project still

00:05:15.940 --> 00:05:21.859
actively developed? And what are the maintenance expectations? Is the package even going to be

00:05:21.859 --> 00:05:26.980
around three years from now when you plan to finish your dissertation? And who else is using

00:05:26.980 --> 00:05:32.339
the software? Is this like an established project? Is there a large user community where you can maybe

00:05:32.339 --> 00:05:39.059
ask questions? So what you do not want is that you become fully dependent on a piece of software

00:05:39.059 --> 00:05:44.420
in your research or in your business. And then at some point, a problem arises and you run into a

00:05:44.420 --> 00:05:50.980
really bad bug or the thing is crashing or it's depending on some other thing that has been retired

00:05:50.980 --> 00:05:56.579
or it just doesn't work anymore on the latest version of Windows or Mac. And then it turns out

00:05:56.579 --> 00:06:02.260
there is no issue tracker. And then you contact the maintainer, but you get no response. Or worse,

00:06:02.260 --> 00:06:08.019
you get a response like, well, this package is part of a research project that no longer exists

00:06:08.019 --> 00:06:12.100
and I've since then transferred to another university and I don't have time to work on

00:06:12.100 --> 00:06:17.779
this anymore. And this happens a lot. I've certainly been there. And it's good to remember

00:06:17.779 --> 00:06:23.380
that the package author really doesn't owe you anything. Most maintainers are very nice and

00:06:23.380 --> 00:06:28.739
very friendly and they're very interested in helping you while also using your feedback to

00:06:28.739 --> 00:06:34.339
improve their package. That is what open source software is all about. But sometimes you find out

00:06:34.339 --> 00:06:40.500
that some software that you were using may actually not be in very good shape. I think a lot of this

00:06:40.500 --> 00:06:46.019
also comes down to the unique life cycle of research software. All software has a life cycle,

00:06:46.019 --> 00:06:52.100
but for open source projects, this is often somewhat unclear and unpredictable. Most

00:06:52.100 --> 00:06:57.940
projects start out as an experiment and then a small fraction of those projects, if it works well

00:06:57.940 --> 00:07:03.779
and the maintainer has enough time to put into it, it may gradually develop into a mature established

00:07:03.779 --> 00:07:11.220
piece of software. But eventually one day all software becomes obsolete and it gets retired

00:07:11.220 --> 00:07:15.859
or replaced with something better. And in commercial projects, there's usually a license

00:07:15.859 --> 00:07:21.059
that states that this product is officially supported until at least 20 blah, blah, blah.

00:07:21.059 --> 00:07:27.380
But in open source projects, there is no such thing. Things are supported basically for the

00:07:27.459 --> 00:07:32.500
extent and the duration that the author has an interest in maintaining that thing.

00:07:33.940 --> 00:07:39.380
For example, a lot of research software only exists as a proof of concept to accompany a

00:07:39.380 --> 00:07:44.100
scientific paper. And once the thing has been published, the author has really no intention

00:07:44.100 --> 00:07:48.980
of ever touching the software again. So if you want to actually build on that software, then

00:07:48.980 --> 00:07:55.140
you're basically on your own. But many R packages these days, they are the exact opposite and they

00:07:55.140 --> 00:08:00.500
are not published for their scientific merit, but they do something very useful. And it is in the

00:08:00.500 --> 00:08:06.579
interest of the package author to get as many people as possible to use the thing to maximize

00:08:06.579 --> 00:08:12.500
the impact of the work. So when we're using a piece of open source software, it can be helpful

00:08:12.500 --> 00:08:20.100
to think for a second about where in the lifecycle this project is. Is this an experiment or a mature

00:08:20.100 --> 00:08:26.019
project? Is it still actively being developed or is it something of the past? So how should we

00:08:26.019 --> 00:08:31.940
handle this? What are things you could look for when you're shopping for R packages? What are

00:08:31.940 --> 00:08:38.900
indicators that reveal something about the health of a project or that may give you a sense of what

00:08:38.900 --> 00:08:45.460
to expect? And what are red flags to avoid common pitfalls? I think we can roughly distinguish

00:08:45.460 --> 00:08:51.140
three categories of indicators. The first category of indicators are technical indicators.

00:08:51.140 --> 00:08:57.219
And those are things that we can measure relatively objectively. So for example, we can

00:08:57.219 --> 00:09:01.859
look at the dependency network and the CRAN homepage of a package already shows you the

00:09:01.859 --> 00:09:06.580
reverse dependencies of a package. And so those are other packages that depend on that package.

00:09:06.580 --> 00:09:11.380
And so that gives you a sense of if the package is trusted by other developers.

00:09:12.099 --> 00:09:16.099
But just counting the number of reverse dependencies doesn't always tell you the

00:09:16.099 --> 00:09:20.900
whole story because some of these reverse dependencies are way more important than others.

00:09:20.900 --> 00:09:26.820
Or sometimes you find a package that is used by 10 other packages all by the same author,

00:09:26.820 --> 00:09:32.020
just like with scientific citations. And so an alternative metric that you could look at

00:09:32.020 --> 00:09:38.979
are to count the recursive reverse dependencies. Or you could weigh the reverse dependencies by

00:09:38.979 --> 00:09:43.380
their own relative importance. So you get something of a page rank statistic.

00:09:44.340 --> 00:09:49.539
And besides dependency relations, other technical indicators that you could look at

00:09:49.539 --> 00:09:56.659
are like download statistics or project activity in terms of releases or commit activity.

00:09:57.460 --> 00:10:03.700
And I think it's especially interesting to look at how these numbers change over time so that you

00:10:03.700 --> 00:10:08.820
get a sense of the lifecycle of a project to see if the product is gaining traction,

00:10:08.820 --> 00:10:14.500
or if it's on its way out, or if it has found like a stable role within the ecosystem.

00:10:15.539 --> 00:10:19.780
Let's actually look at an example that's close to my heart. And this is the curl package.

00:10:19.780 --> 00:10:23.539
So if you need a web client in R, you probably need something with curl bindings.

00:10:23.539 --> 00:10:27.700
But there's actually two CRAN packages that can do this. One is called rcurl and the other one

00:10:27.700 --> 00:10:32.580
is just called curl. So which one should you use? Well, if you look at the CRAN homepage,

00:10:32.580 --> 00:10:38.260
you find a very similar description and even a similar number of reverse dependencies. And you

00:10:38.260 --> 00:10:43.859
can confirm this in R as well. But if we start looking at the recursive reverse dependencies,

00:10:43.859 --> 00:10:48.659
we can see a much bigger difference. And the reason for this is that the curl package is

00:10:48.659 --> 00:10:54.260
used as the foundation for some important web frameworks in R, such as the header package.

00:10:54.820 --> 00:11:00.099
And also, if we look at the reverse dependencies over time, we can see that the use of curl has

00:11:00.099 --> 00:11:06.099
been steadily rising over the past few years, whereas the number of packages that use rcurl

00:11:06.099 --> 00:11:11.539
has been pretty stale. And we can see a similar trend if we look at the download statistics for

00:11:11.539 --> 00:11:17.619
these packages over the years. And the story here is that the rcurl package is very old.

00:11:17.619 --> 00:11:23.859
It has been on CRAN since 2004 and has a paper about it from 2006. And it was some very pioneering

00:11:23.859 --> 00:11:30.179
work at the time. However, a lot has changed since then. And the package has some very fundamental

00:11:30.179 --> 00:11:36.820
problems. And the maintainer of rcurl is not very active anymore. So we wrote the curl package

00:11:36.820 --> 00:11:42.979
specifically as a replacement for rcurl with a modern design to be simpler and more robust.

00:11:42.979 --> 00:11:47.299
And it works very well. And most users have switched over to this new package since then.

00:11:48.340 --> 00:11:53.219
But the old rcurl package is still around. However, it's not in very good shape. And if

00:11:53.219 --> 00:11:58.580
you use it today, you quickly start running into some of these problems. So I think this is one

00:11:58.580 --> 00:12:05.059
example where metrics can help you make a more informed decision and potentially save you a lot

00:12:05.059 --> 00:12:12.580
of problems down the line. But of course, these technical metrics don't always work. For example,

00:12:12.580 --> 00:12:18.340
many R packages are very niche and they're useful only to a very particular specialized group of

00:12:18.340 --> 00:12:24.340
people. So the package may not have many downloads or reverse dependencies. But if this is something

00:12:24.340 --> 00:12:29.539
in your field, it may be exactly what you need. And the second category of indicators I want to

00:12:29.539 --> 00:12:34.979
talk about are social indicators. I consider these to be all the things that have to do something

00:12:34.979 --> 00:12:40.260
with the people behind the project and the way in which the development and the participation

00:12:40.260 --> 00:12:45.780
gets organized. And in my experience, these are by far the most important things to look for

00:12:45.780 --> 00:12:51.619
in a healthy open source project. But these are not easy to quantify. A lot of it just comes down

00:12:51.619 --> 00:12:59.859
to getting to know the community a little bit. So open source projects are, for better or worse,

00:12:59.859 --> 00:13:06.580
most of the time maintained by one or two people. And there's this fantastic book by Nadia Ekpal

00:13:06.580 --> 00:13:11.700
from earlier this year that I really like that talks about the reality behind open source

00:13:11.700 --> 00:13:16.340
development and why this is the case and the consequences that this has. And this is again

00:13:16.340 --> 00:13:21.299
one of those big differences with commercial software. A lot of people are used to thinking

00:13:21.299 --> 00:13:27.940
of software as written by anonymous engineers from a big company. And that is just not how

00:13:27.940 --> 00:13:33.940
it works for us. Open source software is written by people like you and me. And you should think

00:13:33.940 --> 00:13:41.539
of R packages more like a scientific publication or a piece of work by a local artist or a musician.

00:13:42.099 --> 00:13:50.340
It really matters who is making that thing. So the most important social indicator is basically

00:13:50.340 --> 00:13:56.739
who is the author, what organizations they are part of, what people they collaborate with a lot,

00:13:58.340 --> 00:14:02.979
if they're still active or not, and what they're currently working on. And based on the type of

00:14:02.979 --> 00:14:07.460
package, you may care about their formal qualifications and if they have an online

00:14:07.460 --> 00:14:13.059
presence like a blog or a social media. Another social indicator is basically how is the product

00:14:13.059 --> 00:14:18.020
managed. Is there a public place for reporting bugs and do these typically get resolved?

00:14:18.580 --> 00:14:24.020
And if the product is open to contributions from external people and what that process looks like.

00:14:24.580 --> 00:14:29.460
To me, this is very important. I believe every R package should have a public place where everybody

00:14:29.460 --> 00:14:35.460
can post their issues so you can see what problems other users are running into and people can help

00:14:35.460 --> 00:14:41.059
each other out. But let me be clear that you should not expect every R package author to be a

00:14:41.059 --> 00:14:46.739
full-time tech support person. Answering all these questions and reviewing suggestions can be very

00:14:46.739 --> 00:14:52.179
exhausting and sometimes you just don't have time to work on a project for a few days or a few weeks

00:14:52.179 --> 00:15:00.020
or a few months. But for me, the important thing is transparency. If I have no way of seeing what

00:15:00.020 --> 00:15:07.299
are the common problems or questions with a package, that is a red flag. There may be some

00:15:07.299 --> 00:15:14.340
exceptions if the package is relatively small and maintained by a professor that's really the expert

00:15:14.340 --> 00:15:20.900
in the field. It may be okay. But generally speaking, I think a functional issue tracker is

00:15:20.900 --> 00:15:26.979
really a minimal requirement for a healthy open source project. And finally, other social indicators

00:15:26.979 --> 00:15:32.900
you could think of are available resources for learning about the package. For example, if there's

00:15:32.900 --> 00:15:38.979
good documentation either by the package author themselves or by users writing blog posts.

00:15:39.539 --> 00:15:45.299
But for example, also if there's many questions and answers on Stack Overflow, that may be a great

00:15:45.299 --> 00:15:51.380
source of information and a sign that other people are using this package. And then there's a third

00:15:51.380 --> 00:15:56.020
category of indicators and these are perhaps more specific to R because we have a little research

00:15:56.020 --> 00:16:02.739
software. And these are scientific indicators. So for packages that are specifically implementing

00:16:02.739 --> 00:16:08.340
some scientific method, you are probably interested in the validity of those results.

00:16:08.340 --> 00:16:13.539
And for example, if the package is fitting some model, you want to be sure that the estimates are

00:16:13.539 --> 00:16:20.820
accurate and that the package is handling all edge cases properly. And this is of course very difficult

00:16:20.820 --> 00:16:26.580
to judge, but there's some things we can look at. For example, some packages have gone through a

00:16:26.580 --> 00:16:32.340
peer review process. For example, in the Journal of Systical Software or in R OpenSci. That's a

00:16:32.340 --> 00:16:37.859
good sign. It's not a guarantee that the package will be in good standing forever, but at least

00:16:37.859 --> 00:16:43.219
the author has gone through an effort at some point to have a colleague have a critical look at the

00:16:43.219 --> 00:16:51.219
code. And of course, we can look at citations of packages in scientific publications. This is

00:16:51.219 --> 00:16:56.659
very tricky because many researchers don't cite software and if they cite, they probably just cite

00:16:56.659 --> 00:17:04.099
R or tidyverse and not the individual packages. But what is interesting is that many journals

00:17:04.099 --> 00:17:10.260
these days are starting to require researchers to include the analysis code with

00:17:10.260 --> 00:17:16.420
their publication for reproducibility purposes. And so you can imagine if a lot of code becomes

00:17:16.420 --> 00:17:22.819
available this way, we can start to analyze some of this code to see which R packages are

00:17:22.819 --> 00:17:31.219
commonly used in scientific research. So I think the scientific quality of R packages is by far

00:17:31.219 --> 00:17:38.020
the most difficult to judge, but it's very important. All right. So why am I talking about all of this?

00:17:38.739 --> 00:17:44.979
So in R OpenSci, we want to help researchers to get the most out of R. So we do curation and

00:17:44.979 --> 00:17:49.699
we organize peer review of R packages and we provide some development infrastructure.

00:17:50.500 --> 00:17:57.060
And recently, we've been increasingly feeling the need for better tools to actively monitor

00:17:57.060 --> 00:18:06.099
the quality of R packages. And this is both for our internal projects, but also for the R ecosystem

00:18:06.099 --> 00:18:12.579
as a whole, to be able to better advise researchers on what to use. So we've started working on this

00:18:12.579 --> 00:18:17.939
new project called R Universe. And on the one hand, R Universe is an extension of our internal

00:18:17.939 --> 00:18:23.380
build infrastructure. So in R OpenSci, we have a doc server, which automatically builds package

00:18:23.380 --> 00:18:28.500
documentation for all of our packages. And we have a CRAN-like server, which automatically

00:18:28.500 --> 00:18:33.380
builds the binaries for all of our packages. And this works very well. And with R Universe, we

00:18:33.380 --> 00:18:39.540
basically want to enable other organizations to take advantage of this same tooling. But we want

00:18:39.540 --> 00:18:46.339
R Universe to not become just a build system, but also a place where you can learn more about these

00:18:46.339 --> 00:18:51.140
packages. And so we're going to try to combine some of these hard data that you get from the build

00:18:51.140 --> 00:18:58.180
system with other sources of information about authors and activity and the life cycle and all

00:18:58.180 --> 00:19:03.300
these things that we've talked about. And then we have someone else to work on the scientific metrics.

00:19:03.380 --> 00:19:10.420
So they are developing tools that can help us find citations and mentions of packages in scientific

00:19:10.420 --> 00:19:16.339
publications. And besides showing information about a single project, we also want to help with

00:19:16.339 --> 00:19:24.020
the discovery of other software. And so by cross-referencing similar packages or other work by

00:19:24.020 --> 00:19:29.219
the same author or the same organization, maybe we can build something of a recommender system.

00:19:30.020 --> 00:19:36.900
And finally, we want this to be a place that says something about the impact and the

00:19:36.900 --> 00:19:45.300
importance of an R project in order to help package authors get credit for research software

00:19:45.300 --> 00:19:50.900
in the same way as this happens for scientific publications. So this was my talk. Thank you for

00:19:50.900 --> 00:19:56.260
listening. I hope I got you thinking a little bit about the world behind open source development.

00:19:57.140 --> 00:20:00.979
And if I got you interested in the R-Universe project, keep an eye on our website,

00:20:00.979 --> 00:20:06.420
r-universe.dev, where we will start adding more of the things that we're working on

00:20:06.420 --> 00:20:08.339
over the upcoming year.

